A trade I make that complies with the rigid requirements of my trading protocol is a good trade -- it may or may not be a profitable trade. People who do not understand this basically do not understand market speculation
The measure of a trade is not whether or not it makes money. A "good" trade can lose money. An "ill conceived" trade can be profitable.

7/ In the rapidly evolving cryptoasset space, this subsection seems to evolve even quicker. Adapt or get left behind.

6/ With so many ICOs coming out daily, and a massive discrepancy in hype between projects but not necessarily potential value...there will be opportunities even for those that missed sales but are still able to find ICOs with undervalued mkt cap when they hit exchange.

5/ The risk:reward ratio of ICOs is incredibly attractive. The largest risk investing in ICOs is the liquidity risk. You are investing in a token/coin that is not tradeable yet (and may never be). Still - the risk:reward is very favorable currently. e.g. make 2-50x or lose 50%

4/ Whether you agree with it or not, projects are looking to investors that can provide more than capital. For example: -legal or any structuring service -investors/funds with influence -connections to exchanges -investors that can introduce them to people they need access to
3/ I'm sure many active ICO investors have realized that less and less of each raise is going to the public more here: https:// twitter.com/VentureCoinist /status/956594823892357120 …
2/ *none of this is financial advise or a recommendation to invest in ICOs. DYOR and find a strategy that is suitable for you.

1/ Some updated thoughts on the state of the current ICO cycle -> Less being raised in public sales -> Investors that can provide more than capital will start earning more allocation -> The risk:reward ratio -> Strategy even if you missed the initial sale

To answer this: I do not believe for one second that Nunes is sincere.

But apply that same standard to Trump - and dear God, the outrage. What mystifies me is why people who once insisted on the paramount role of character aren’t leading the charge, and mod-cons like me have to be the ones to point out the moral abyss the GOP now lives in.

And I have taken a ton of crap for never wavering about her awfulness, even when I advocated the necessity of voting for her, and I think the average voters who admire her are dumb, deluded, or in some cases, disingenuous.

Did you say: “Well, these are nice people who truly believe this for good reasons,” or did you think of them as deluded, deceived, sometimes lying, and some even corrupt? Because I regard the Hillary cult much as I do the Trump cult.

Well, let me ask you. What did think of people who talked about what a terrific public servant Hillary Clinton was, describing her sterling character, her faith and moral fiber, her integrity, and how she was a champion and role model for women? /1
